PAINTING
NEWS
In dialogue: The Louvre looting
Substackers consider the strangely chic crime heard round the world: the th=
eft of France=E2=80=99s crown jewels.
Sloane Crosley [ https://substack.com/redirect/faa311f7-deb8-4ef6-b654-63e3=
77b95c62?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3y=
s ]: Every once in a while, a story comes along formed by a perfect synergy=
 of comprehensible crime and real-time intrigue. These moments are like pre=
cious stones, and the internet goes berserk for them. One such tale began o=
n Sunday, when robbers smashed a Seine-adjacent gallery window of the Louvr=
e and made off with eight pieces of historically priceless jewelry.
Clara [ https://substack.com/redirect/1d5507a4-25a8-4771-abbc-6ebd6baa0c4b?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ]: Who =
needs yoga or deep breathing exercises when we have French heists of Napole=
onic jewels to read about.
Maisa [ https://substack.com/redirect/6f60b811-d697-4530-b598-b6ceb9300991?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ]: Some=
one walked into the Louvre=E2=80=94in broad daylight=E2=80=94spent roughly =
the length of a rushed matcha run in a jewellery case, and walked out momen=
ts later with the French Crown Jewels.
Jo Piazza [ https://substack.com/redirect/5997ae0a-5fa6-444e-9f6c-ef6dd411a=
1a0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ]: =
France=E2=80=99s ministry of culture said the stolen items were:
A tiara and brooch belonging to Empress Eug=C3=A9nie, wife of Napoleon III
An emerald necklace and a pair of emerald earrings from Empress Marie Louis=
e
A tiara, necklace and single earring from the sapphire set that belonged to=
 Queen Marie-Am=C3=A9lie and Queen Hortense
A brooch known as the =E2=80=9Creliquary brooch=E2=80=9D
Maisa [ https://substack.com/redirect/6f60b811-d697-4530-b598-b6ceb9300991?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ]: They=
 arrived in a lift, left on scooters, and=E2=80=94according to one witness=
=E2=80=94stopped at a red light on their way home. That=E2=80=99s not just =
audacity, that=E2=80=99s etiquette.
Clara [ https://substack.com/redirect/1d5507a4-25a8-4771-abbc-6ebd6baa0c4b?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ]: Cons=
idering the loneliness epidemic and the anti-intellectualism we find oursel=
ves traversing as a society, it=E2=80=99s nice to see a group of friends ge=
t together and make museum plans for a Saturday morning. Gives a girl a bit=
 of hope.
Jo Piazza [ https://substack.com/redirect/5997ae0a-5fa6-444e-9f6c-ef6dd411a=
1a0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ]: =
All of the stolen pieces are part of the national Crown Jewels collection, =
which means they aren=E2=80=99t privately insured (fascinating detail!). Re=
covery efforts began within hours, because once the jewelry is broken down =
into individual gems, they=E2=80=99re gonna be almost impossible to trace.
Clara [ https://substack.com/redirect/1d5507a4-25a8-4771-abbc-6ebd6baa0c4b?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ]: Like=
, I suspect, many other people, I guess I harbor a tiny bit of fascination =
with art heists=E2=80=94conceptually speaking, of course.
Sloane Crosley [ https://substack.com/redirect/faa311f7-deb8-4ef6-b654-63e3=
77b95c62?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3y=
s ]: It=E2=80=99s not that people are salivating at the idea of criminality=
, but some are agnostic about=E2=80=94nay, amused by=E2=80=94the robbery. P=
art of this is because fires aren=E2=80=99t funny and heists kind of are. T=
hey are painted as sexy, madcap or soulful in pop culture (=E2=80=9COcean=
=E2=80=99s Eleven,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CThe Thomas Crown Affair,=E2=80=9D even=
 =E2=80=9CThe Goldfinch=E2=80=9D).
Maisa [ https://substack.com/redirect/6f60b811-d697-4530-b598-b6ceb9300991?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ]: A mu=
seum heist is so deliciously whimsical. It=E2=80=99s the cardigan of crimes=
, dashing, polite, borderline literary. Nobody=E2=80=99s grandma loses her =
pension, no innocent bystander is traumatized, and nothing explodes except =
the collective imagination. This is the sort of news story that reads like =
a short film: four shadowy figures, a perfect plan, and a little red-light =
courtesy on the getaway.
Jo Piazza [ https://substack.com/redirect/5997ae0a-5fa6-444e-9f6c-ef6dd411a=
1a0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ]: =
There were no smoke bombs or cinematic laser grids or someone dropping in f=
rom a ceiling. Just four people who understood museum security and knew the=
ir way around construction equipment and power tools.
Maisa [ https://substack.com/redirect/6f60b811-d697-4530-b598-b6ceb9300991?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ]: Of c=
ourse this is satire, I=E2=80=99m not advocating for crime. But the romanti=
cism of it, the elegance, the precision, that=E2=80=99s undeniably seductiv=
e. It=E2=80=99s proof that imagination still exists in a world allergic to =
surprise. In an era of scams and data leaks and faceless corruption, a good=
 old-fashioned jewel heist feels almost wholesome.
PHOTOGRAPHY
HISTORY
Revolutionary media
Theo Lipsky on how the American Revolution was fueled not by scholarly trea=
tises but by =E2=80=9Camateurish, at times reductive pamphlets=E2=80=9D=E2=
=80=94the viral content of their day.
Topical, Polemical, Short [ https://substack.com/redirect/673d22ba-db2c-411=
b-8ae6-03d2e4e6340c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9=
ecHmePkbA3ys ]
=E2=80=94Theo Lipsky  in Garrison Notes =20
Bailyn=E2=80=99s point is that most of the revolutionaries were not inspire=
d by what we today might call =E2=80=9Cdeep reads.=E2=80=9D Instead, the in=
tellectual prime mover of the American Revolution was a corpus of amateuris=
h, at times reductive pamphlets, given to disquiet and written for mass con=
sumption. The Revolutionary-era pamphlets may now seem to have merely popul=
arized or synthesized more important original thinkers, but Bailyn argues t=
he extraordinary element at work was the rhetoric of the pamphlets themselv=
es.
These pamphlets were in some ways familiar to us. They were accessible. The=
y were grandiose. They came laden with cartoons. They were sarcastic. They =
were allegorical. They could spin out into long, acid exchanges and feuds b=
etween competing authors. And they peddled, for lack of a better term, cons=
piracy theories. Or so argues Bailyn:
The danger to America, it was believed, was in fact only the small, immedia=
tely visible part of the greater whole whose ultimate manifestation would b=
e the destruction of the English constitution, with all the rights and priv=
ileges embedded in it. This belief transformed the meaning of the colonists=
=E2=80=99 struggle, and it added an inner accelerator to the movement of op=
position. For, once assumed, it could not easily be dispelled: denial only =
confirmed it, since what the conspirators profess is not what they believe;=
 the ostensible is not the real; and the real is deliberately malign.
None of this is to say that John Adams suffered the same strand of brainrot=
 now apparently rampant thanks to the exquisitely designed user interfaces =
of most media platforms. It=E2=80=99s just to say that today=E2=80=99s read=
ers are not alone in confronting a froth of fractious, charged, imprecise a=
nd conspiratorial stuff. Ironically, Bailyn says, the colonists read the au=
thors of classical antiquity not to commune with antiquity on its own terms=
 but because those authors, if narrowly understood, appeared to share the c=
olonists=E2=80=99 concerns:
They had hated and feared the trends of their own time, and in their writin=
g had contrasted the present with a better past, which they endowed with qu=
alities absent from their own, corrupt era. The earlier age had been full o=
f virtue: simplicity, patriotism, integrity, a love of justice and of liber=
ty; the present was venal, cynical and oppressive.
It=E2=80=99s hard not to detect today a similar wistfulness about the past.=
 One can take this either as dispiriting or reassuring=E2=80=94either thing=
s have always been that bad or things are better than they seem. The warm i=
ntelligence of Bailyn=E2=80=99s work is at least one reason to choose the l=
atter.
